  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "Choosing the right books can significantly enhance your understanding of economics beyond classroom lectures. Here are three highly recommended books for an undergraduate studying economics:\n\n1. **\"Capital in the Twenty-First Century\" by Thomas Piketty**\n\n   *Overview:* This seminal work delves into the dynamics of wealth and income inequality over the past few centuries. Piketty uses extensive historical data to analyze the concentration of wealth and its implications for economic growth and social stability.\n\n   *Why Read It:* Understanding inequality is crucial for modern economics. Piketty's analysis provides valuable insights into how economic policies can influence wealth distribution, making it essential for students interested in macroeconomics, public policy, and economic history.\n\n2. **\"The Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith**\n\n   *Overview:* Published in 1776, this classic lays the foundational principles of classical economics. Smith explores topics such as division of labor, free markets, and the \"invisible hand\" that guides economic prosperity.\n\n   *Why Read It:* As one of the fundamental texts in economic thought, it offers historical context and a deep understanding of market dynamics. Reading Smith will give you a solid grounding in the principles that underpin much of modern economic theory.\n\n3. **\"Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything\" by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner**\n\n   *Overview:* This engaging book applies economic theory to diverse and unconventional topics, uncovering surprising truths about human behavior and societal trends.\n\n   *Why Read It:* \"Freakonomics\" demonstrates the versatility of economic thinking and encourages critical analysis of everyday phenomena. It's particularly useful for developing analytical skills and understanding how to apply economic principles to real-world situations.\n\n---\n\n**Honorable Mentions:**\n\n- **\"Thinking, Fast and Slow\" by Daniel Kahneman:** While primarily a psychology book, it offers valuable insights into behavioral economics and decision-making processes.\n  \n- **\"Economics\" by Paul Samuelson and William Nordhaus:** A comprehensive textbook that covers a wide range of economic theories and applications, suitable for reinforcing academic knowledge.\n\n- **\"Nudge: Improving Decisions About Health, Wealth, and Happiness\" by Richard H. Thaler and Cass R. Sunstein:** Explores how behavioral economics can inform policy-making and personal decisions.\n\nThese books collectively provide a blend of theoretical knowledge, historical perspective, and practical application, equipping you with a well-rounded understanding of economics.",
